was initially described 105 years ago (
2
), and for most of the 20th century tyrannosaurs were known almost solely from fossils of
T . rex
and four closely related species of large, multi-ton Late Cretaceous predators (
3
). Within the last decade, however, the diversity of tyrannosaurs has more than doubled, and during the past year alone, six new species were described, some of which are 100 million years older and 1/100 the size of
T . rex
(
